default2
default survey in which 
default1,943 
defaulthouseholds were interviewed. All adults questioned in the Family Resources Survey were asked about the types of accounts they have held over the last 12 months. 
default&#xa0;
defaultT
defaulthe numbers of people/households with access to bank accounts is an important indicator for financial inclusion. The Consumer Council’s ‘Price of Being Poor’
default report shows that consumers on low incomes that cannot access mainstream financial services end up paying more, a “poverty premium”, for the services they need (for example, higher gas and electricity bills because they cannot get direct debit discounts). 
default&#xa0;
defaultTable
default 4.1 
defaulton the following page 
defaultshows the percentage of households with one or more current, savings or investment accounts and those with one or more direct payment accounts, including and excluding Post Office Card Accounts (POCAs).  This has been measured across all areas of GB and NI. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA POCA allows c
defaultonsumers to withdraw cash at the Post Office but there are no facilities to set up direct debits to manage money and pay bills.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTable 4.1 shows that 
default1
default1
default per cent of households in NI do not have a current account with access to direct debit and overdraft facilities.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt also shows that 
defaultonly 
default9
default4
default per cent of households in NI had
default any type of
default account including POCAs
default, a figure down 1 per cent since the last survey
default. This was the lowest proportion for any region in the UK, an
defaultd compared to a UK average of 98
default per cent. 
